VALUES
(43, 7, 1, 43, 5, 16, 18, 'sought to kill him', 'Persecution of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the Jews'' intent to kill Jesus due to his actions and claims. In John 5:16-18, the Jews sought to slay him for healing on the Sabbath, while John 7:1 indicates their ongoing pursuit of him in Galilee.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 1, 43, 4, 3, 3, 'he would not walk in Jewry', 'Jesus'' Movement Between Regions', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' movement in Galilee and Judea. The first passage indicates his avoidance of Judea due to threats, while the second shows his departure from Judea to Galilee.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 1, 40, 21, 38, 38, 'sought to kill him', 'Connection of Rejection and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the intent to kill Jesus, highlighting the rejection he faced. In John 7:1, the Jews sought to kill him, while in Matthew 21:38, the husbandmen plot to kill the son, indicating a parallel theme of hostility towards God''s messengers.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 1, 40, 10, 23, 23, 'sought to kill him', 'Persecution and Fleeing', 'This connection highlights the theme of persecution faced by Jesus and his followers. Both passages emphasize the need to avoid danger and seek safety in the face of threats, as seen in Jesus'' actions and his instructions to his disciples.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 1, 44, 10, 38, 38, 'he would not walk in Jewry', 'Jesus'' Ministry and Opposition', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' active ministry in Galilee while facing opposition from the Jews who sought to kill him. Both passages emphasize Jesus'' actions and the divine support he received, showcasing his mission to heal and do good despite threats.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 1, 42, 13, 31, 33, 'he would not walk in Jewry', 'Jesus'' Danger and Mission', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' awareness of threats to his life. Both passages emphasize the danger he faces, with John noting that ''the Jews sought to kill him'' and Luke mentioning Herod''s intent to kill him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 2, 38, 14, 16, 19, 'feast of tabernacles', 'Feast of Tabernacles Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the feast of tabernacles. John 7:2 mentions the feast being at hand, while Zechariah 14:16-19 describes its future observance by nations, highlighting its importance in worship.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 2, 5, 16, 13, 16, 'feast of tabernacles', 'Connection of Feast of Tabernacles', 'Both passages emphasize the ''feast of tabernacles'' as a significant celebration. John 7:2 mentions the timing of this feast, while Deuteronomy 16:13-16 outlines its observance and importance in the Israelite tradition.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 2, 2, 23, 16, 17, 'feast of tabernacles', 'Connection of Feast References', 'This connection highlights the significance of the ''feast'' mentioned in both passages. John 7:2 refers to the ''feast of tabernacles,'' which aligns with the ''feast of ingathering'' in Exodus 23:16-17, emphasizing the importance of harvest celebrations.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 2, 3, 23, 34, 43, 'feast of tabernacles', 'Feast of Tabernacles Connection', 'This connection highlights the observance of the feast of tabernacles in both passages. John 7:2 references the timing of the feast, while Leviticus 23:34-43 provides detailed instructions for its celebration.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 2, 4, 29, 12, 38, 'feast of tabernacles', 'Feast of Tabernacles Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the feast, with John referencing the ''feast of tabernacles'' and Numbers detailing the specific offerings and observances associated with it. This connection highlights the continuity of worship practices in Israel.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 2, 11, 8, 2, 2, 'feast of tabernacles', 'Feast Timing Connection', 'Both passages emphasize a significant feast occurring in the seventh month. John 7:2 refers to the feast of tabernacles, which aligns with the timing mentioned in 1 Kings 8:2.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 2, 11, 8, 65, 65, 'feast of tabernacles', 'Feasts in Biblical Context', 'Both passages emphasize significant feasts in Israel''s history. John 7:2 mentions the feast of tabernacles, while 1 Kings 8:65 describes a great feast held by Solomon. This connection highlights the importance of communal worship and celebration in the Jewish tradition.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 3, 40, 12, 46, 46, 'his brethren', 'Family Interaction with Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Jesus'' brethren and their desire to engage with him. In John 7:3, they encourage him to go to Judea, while in Matthew 12:46, they seek to speak with him, highlighting their ongoing involvement in his ministry.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 3, 43, 7, 5, 5, 'His brethren therefore said unto him', 'Skepticism of Jesus'' Brethren', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the encouragement of Jesus'' brethren to go to Judea and their lack of belief in him. While they urge him to show his works, it is noted that they did not believe in him, emphasizing their skepticism.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 3, 1, 37, 5, 11, NULL, 'Sibling Rivalry and Dreams', 'Both passages emphasize the tension between siblings, as seen in Joseph''s dreams and the disdain from his brethren in Genesis, paralleling the skepticism of Jesus'' brothers in John. This connection highlights the theme of familial conflict arising from perceived superiority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 3, 1, 37, 20, 20, NULL, 'Sibling Betrayal and Ambition', 'This connection highlights the theme of sibling dynamics and ambition. In John 7:3, Jesus'' brothers urge him to display his works, paralleling the brothers in Genesis 37:20 who plot against Joseph''s dreams.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 3, 9, 17, 28, 28, NULL, 'Sibling Reproach and Motivation', 'This connection highlights the theme of sibling reproach, where both passages depict brothers questioning the motivations of a younger sibling. In John 7:3, the brethren urge Jesus to display his works, while in 1 Samuel 17:28, Eliab accuses David of coming to see the battle. Both instances reflect a misunderstanding of the younger sibling''s intentions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 3, 24, 12, 6, 6, 'brethren', 'Betrayal by Brethren', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal by family members. In both passages, the actions and words of brethren are depicted as treacherous or misleading.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 3, 40, 22, 16, 17, 'thy disciples also may see', 'Disciples and Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of disciples seeking Jesus'' authority. In John 7:3, the brethren encourage Jesus to show his works to his disciples, while in Matthew 22:16-17, the disciples of the Pharisees approach Jesus to question him about authority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 4, 43, 18, 20, 20, 'doeth any thing in secret', 'Openness in Jesus'' Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of openness in Jesus'' actions and teachings. In John 7:4, the call to show oneself openly parallels Jesus'' assertion in John 18:20 that he taught openly and in public spaces.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 4, 20, 18, 1, 2, 'seeketh to be known openly', 'Desire for Public Recognition', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeking recognition and understanding. Both passages discuss the desire to be known and the pursuit of wisdom, contrasting the motivations of those who seek to reveal themselves versus those who lack understanding.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 4, 40, 6, 5, 5, 'seeketh to be known openly', 'Public vs. Private Actions', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between actions done in secret and those intended for public recognition. John 7:4 discusses seeking to be known openly, while Matthew 6:5 warns against praying for the sake of being seen by others.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 4, 40, 23, 5, 5, 'shew thyself to the world', 'Public Display of Actions', 'This connection highlights the theme of performing actions for public recognition. Both passages emphasize the desire to be seen by others, whether through open displays or the enlargement of religious symbols.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 4, 42, 6, 45, 45, 'shew thyself to the world', 'Connection of Intent and Action', 'This connection highlights the relationship between outward actions and inner motivations. Both passages emphasize that what is revealed externally reflects the true nature of one''s heart.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 4, 11, 22, 13, 13, 'shew thyself to the world', 'Public Declarations and Expectations', 'This connection highlights the expectation of public affirmation in both passages. John 7:4 emphasizes the desire to be known openly, while 1 Kings 22:13 reflects the pressure to conform to popular opinion among prophets.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 4, 44, 2, 4, 12, 'shew thyself to the world', 'Public Revelation of God''s Works', 'This connection highlights the theme of public demonstration. In John 7:4, the call to ''shew thyself to the world'' parallels the public display of the Holy Spirit''s power in Acts 2:4-12, where the apostles speak in tongues, revealing God''s works to a diverse audience.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 5, 41, 3, 21, 21, 'for neither did his brethren believe in him.', 'Unbelief of Jesus'' Family', 'This connection highlights the theme of disbelief surrounding Jesus. In John 7:5, his brethren''s lack of belief is echoed in Mark 3:21, where friends express concern for his mental state, suggesting a similar lack of understanding and belief.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 5, 43, 1, 11, 13, NULL, 'Rejection of Jesus by His Own', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection in both passages. John 7:5 states that ''his brethren did not believe in him,'' paralleling John 1:11''s assertion that ''his own received him not.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 5, 33, 7, 5, 6, 'neither did his brethren believe in him', 'Family Betrayal and Distrust', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of betrayal within familial relationships. John 7:5 highlights the lack of belief from Jesus'' own brethren, while Micah 7:5-6 describes how family members can become enemies, reflecting a deep-seated distrust.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 5, 43, 7, 3, 3, 'his brethren', 'Skepticism of Jesus'' Brethren', 'This connection highlights the skepticism of Jesus'' brethren, as they encourage him to go to Judea while indicating their lack of belief. The statement in John 7:5 reinforces their disbelief, suggesting a contrast between their actions and true faith.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 5, 43, 7, 10, 10, NULL, 'Brethren''s Unbelief and Secrecy', 'This connection highlights the lack of belief in Jesus by his brethren, which sets the stage for their departure to the feast. Their disbelief contrasts with Jesus'' decision to go up secretly, indicating a tension between their actions and his.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 6, 43, 2, 4, 4, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus'' Timing', 'Both passages emphasize that Jesus'' ''hour'' or ''time'' has not yet come, indicating a theme of divine timing in His ministry. This connection highlights the significance of timing in Jesus'' actions and responses.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 6, 43, 7, 8, 8, 'my time is not yet come', 'Timing of Jesus'' Actions', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of timing in relation to Jesus'' actions. In each instance, Jesus states that ''my time is not yet come,'' indicating a deliberate control over when he will reveal himself.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 6, 40, 26, 18, 18, 'My time is not yet come', 'Timing of Jesus'' Mission', 'This connection highlights the theme of timing in Jesus'' ministry. In John 7:6, Jesus indicates that His time has not yet come, while in Matthew 26:18, He declares that His time is at hand, marking a significant shift in His mission.', 'theme', 0.986, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 6, 44, 1, 7, 7, 'my time is not yet come', 'Timing and Divine Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of timing in both passages. Jesus indicates that his time has not yet come, while in Acts, it is stated that the knowledge of times is under the Father''s authority.', 'theme', 0.671, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 6, 19, 102, 13, 13, 'my time is not yet come', 'Timing of Divine Favor', 'This connection highlights the theme of ''time'' in both passages. John 7:6 speaks of Jesus'' time not yet being fulfilled, while Psalms 102:13 declares that the set time to favor Zion has come.', 'theme', 0.643, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 6, 21, 3, 1, 15, 'My time is not yet come', 'Connection of Timing and Purpose', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of timing in relation to purpose. Jesus indicates that his time has not yet come, while Ecclesiastes discusses the appropriate time for various human activities.', 'theme', 0.629, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 7, 43, 15, 18, 19, NULL, 'Connection of World Hatred', 'Both passages emphasize the world''s hatred towards Jesus and His followers. The phrase ''the world hateth you'' in John 15:18 directly relates to the assertion in John 7:7 that ''the world cannot hate you; but me it hateth.''', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 7, 43, 3, 19, 19, 'that the works thereof are evil', 'Connection of Evil Deeds', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of evil deeds. In John 7:7, Jesus testifies that the works of the world are evil, while John 3:19 states that men loved darkness because their deeds were evil.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 7, 48, 4, 16, 16, 'because I testify of it, that the works thereof are evil', 'Truth and Hatred Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of truth leading to hostility. In John, Jesus is hated for testifying against evil, while in Galatians, Paul questions if he has become an enemy for speaking the truth.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 7, 20, 9, 7, 8, 'the works thereof are evil', 'Connection of Hatred and Rebuke', 'This connection highlights the theme of hatred towards those who confront evil. Both passages emphasize the negative response to reproof, with John noting that the world hates him for testifying against its evil works, while Proverbs warns against reproving a scorner, who will respond with hatred.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 7, 59, 4, 4, 4, 'the world cannot hate you', 'World''s Hatred and Enmity', 'Both passages emphasize the conflict between the world and God. John 7:7 highlights that the world hates Jesus for exposing its evil, while James 4:4 states that friendship with the world equates to enmity with God.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 7, 62, 4, 5, 5, 'the world cannot hate you', 'Connection of Worldly Reception', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between the world and those who testify to its evil. John 7:7 highlights the world''s hatred for Jesus due to His testimony, while 1 John 4:5 indicates that those of the world speak in ways the world accepts.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 7, 11, 21, 20, 20, 'works thereof are evil', 'Evil Works and Hatred', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of evil actions leading to animosity. In John, the speaker''s testimony about evil works incites hatred, while in 1 Kings, Ahab''s evil actions provoke Elijah''s confrontation.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 8, 43, 7, 6, 6, NULL, 'Connection of Timing in John', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''time'' in relation to Jesus'' actions. Jesus indicates that His timing is not yet fulfilled, contrasting it with the readiness of others.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 8, 43, 8, 20, 20, 'my time is not yet full come', 'Timing of Jesus'' Actions', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of timing in Jesus'' ministry. In John 7:8, Jesus states, ''my time is not yet full come,'' while in John 8:20, it is noted that ''his hour was not yet come.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 8, 43, 7, 30, 30, 'my time is not yet full come', 'Connection of Timing in John', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of timing in relation to Jesus'' actions. In John 7:8, Jesus indicates that his time has not yet come, while in John 7:30, it is stated that his hour was not yet come, highlighting a consistent theme of divine timing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 8, 46, 2, 15, 16, 'my time is not yet full come', 'Understanding Timing and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of timing and discernment. In John 7:8, the phrase ''my time is not yet full come'' suggests a divine timing, while 1 Corinthians 2:15-16 emphasizes the spiritual discernment of those who possess ''the mind of Christ.''', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 8, 43, 11, 6, 7, 'my time is not yet full come', 'Timing of Jesus'' Actions', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' timing in both passages. In John 7:8, Jesus indicates that ''my time is not yet full come,'' while in John 11:6-7, he chooses to delay his response to Lazarus'' sickness, demonstrating his control over the timing of events.', 'theme', 0.293, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 10, 30, 5, 13, 13, 'not openly, but as it were in secret', 'Silence in Evil Times', 'This connection highlights the theme of discretion in challenging circumstances. Both passages emphasize the need for caution and silence in times perceived as evil or dangerous.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 10, 40, 10, 16, 16, 'as it were in secret', 'Wisdom in Secrecy', 'This connection highlights the theme of being cautious and strategic in one''s actions. In John 7:10, Jesus goes to the feast ''as it were in secret,'' while Matthew 10:16 advises being ''wise as serpents'' in a hostile environment.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 10, 23, 42, 2, 3, 'as it were in secret', 'Connection of Secrecy and Gentleness', 'This connection highlights the theme of subtlety in both passages. John 7:10 mentions Jesus going up ''in secret,'' while Isaiah 42:2-3 describes a gentle approach, emphasizing quietness and care.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 10, 19, 26, 8, 8, NULL, 'Connection of Worship and Secrecy', 'This connection highlights the theme of reverence for God''s house. In John 7:10, Jesus goes to the feast in secret, while Psalms 26:8 expresses love for the habitation of God''s house, suggesting a deep respect for sacred spaces.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 10, 19, 40, 8, 8, NULL, 'Connection of Will and Action', 'This connection highlights the theme of obedience to God''s will. In John 7:10, Jesus acts in secret, suggesting a deliberate choice to fulfill his mission, while Psalms 40:8 expresses a delight in doing God''s will, indicating a heart aligned with divine purpose.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 10, 40, 3, 15, 15, NULL, 'Fulfillment of Righteousness', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus acting in accordance with divine purpose. In both passages, Jesus engages in significant actions—going to the feast in secret and fulfilling righteousness through baptism—demonstrating his commitment to God''s plan.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 10, 43, 7, 3, 3, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus'' Actions', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' movement towards Judea. In John 7:3, his brethren encourage him to go, while in John 7:10, he goes secretly after they leave.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 11, 43, 11, 56, 56, 'sought him at the feast', 'Seeking Jesus at the Feast', 'Both passages emphasize the act of seeking Jesus during the feast. In each instance, the people are questioning his presence and discussing whether he will come, highlighting their anticipation and curiosity about him.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 12, 43, 7, 40, 43, 'there was much murmuring among the people', 'Division Among the People', 'Both passages emphasize the division among the people regarding Jesus'' identity. In the first passage, some call him a good man while others accuse him of deception, and in the second, opinions vary on whether he is the Prophet or the Christ, leading to further division.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 12, 43, 9, 16, 16, NULL, 'Division Among People and Leaders', 'This connection highlights the theme of division among people regarding Jesus'' identity. In both passages, some view him positively, while others reject him, demonstrating the ongoing conflict and differing opinions about his nature and actions.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 12, 40, 10, 25, 25, 'deceiveth the people', 'Perception of Jesus and His Followers', 'Both passages emphasize the division in public opinion about Jesus. In John 7:12, some view him as a good man while others see him as deceiving the people, paralleling Matthew 10:25, which suggests that if Jesus is called Beelzebub, his followers will face similar accusations.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 12, 40, 16, 13, 16, 'He is a good man', 'Public Perception of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize differing opinions about Jesus. In John 7:12, some view him as a good man, while in Matthew 16:13-16, the disciples report various identities attributed to him, reflecting the confusion and debate surrounding his true nature.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 12, 42, 6, 45, 45, 'He is a good man', 'Goodness and Deception Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the distinction between a good man and one who deceives. John 7:12 presents conflicting views on Jesus'' character, while Luke 6:45 explains that a good man brings forth good from his heart. This connection highlights the moral evaluation of individuals based on their actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 12, 42, 7, 16, 16, 'He is a good man', 'Perception of Jesus as Prophet', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s reactions to Jesus, with some viewing him as a good man and others as a deceiver. In Luke, the acknowledgment of Jesus as a great prophet reflects a similar division in opinion found in John.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 12, 44, 11, 24, 24, 'He is a good man', 'Good Man Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the characterization of a ''good man.'' In John 7:12, some people debate whether Jesus is a good man, while Acts 11:24 explicitly describes Barnabas as a good man, highlighting a positive perception of his character.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 13, 43, 9, 22, 22, 'fear of the Jews', 'Fear of the Jews', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of the Jews, which leads individuals to silence about Jesus. In John 7:13, the fear prevents open discussion, while in John 9:22, it causes the parents to deny their son''s confession of Christ.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 13, 43, 19, 38, 38, 'for fear of the Jews', 'Fear of the Jews', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of the Jews that led to secrecy in the actions of Jesus'' followers. In John 7:13, people spoke openly about Jesus only with fear, while in John 19:38, Joseph of Arimathea acted secretly for the same reason.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 13, 20, 29, 25, 25, 'fear of the Jews', 'Fear and Trust in God', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear in both passages. John 7:13 mentions fear of the Jews, while Proverbs 29:25 states that ''the fear of man bringeth a snare,'' contrasting it with trust in the Lord.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 13, 48, 2, 12, 13, NULL, 'Fear of Social Repercussions', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fear influencing behavior. In John 7:13, fear of the Jews prevents open discussion about Jesus, while in Galatians 2:12-13, fear of the circumcision leads Peter to withdraw from Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 13, 55, 2, 9, 13, 'fear of the Jews', 'Fear and Suffering for Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering for faith. In John 7:13, fear of the Jews leads to silence about Jesus, while 2 Timothy 2:9-13 discusses enduring suffering for the sake of the Gospel. Both passages emphasize the challenges faced by believers in proclaiming their faith.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 13, 66, 2, 13, 13, 'for fear of the Jews', 'Fear and Faith Amidst Persecution', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear in the face of persecution, as seen in John 7:13 where people spoke ''for fear of the Jews.'' Similarly, Revelation 2:13 acknowledges the faithfulness of believers despite the presence of ''Satan''s seat'' and the martyrdom of Antipas. Both passages emphasize the struggle of maintaining faith amidst societal pressures.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 14, 43, 7, 28, 28, 'taught', 'Jesus Teaching in the Temple', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' active role in teaching during the feast, as noted in both passages. The emphasis on his teaching in the temple underscores his authority and the revelation of his true identity.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 14, 42, 19, 47, 47, NULL, 'Teaching in the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' teaching in the temple. In John 7:14, he begins teaching during a feast, while in Luke 19:47, he continues to teach daily, indicating a consistent presence and message in the temple.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 14, 43, 8, 2, 2, 'taught', 'Teaching in the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' teaching in the temple. In John 7:14, he begins teaching during the feast, and in John 8:2, he continues this teaching the next morning, highlighting his role as a teacher.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
